Note:
Runa Standard Library: Fractions Module

Provides comprehensive rational number arithmetic with high precision and AI-friendly
interfaces. Supports all basic arithmetic operations, advanced mathematical functions,
and specialized features for AI-to-AI communication.

Features:
- Exact rational arithmetic with unlimited precision
- All basic arithmetic operations (+, -, *, /, **)
- Advanced mathematical functions
- Comparison and ordering operations
- Conversion to/from other numeric types
- AI-friendly interfaces and metadata
- Performance optimizations
- Error handling and validation
:End Note

Note: Core Types and Constants
Type Fraction is Dictionary with:
    numerator as Integer
    denominator as Integer
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type FractionResult is:
    | FractionSuccess with value as Fraction
    | FractionError with message as String and code as String

Type FractionFormat is:
    | DECIMAL
    | RATIONAL
    | MIXED
    | SCIENTIFIC
    | AI_FRIENDLY

Type FractionOptions is Dictionary with:
    simplify_automatically as Boolean defaults to true
    allow_zero_denominator as Boolean defaults to false
    max_precision as Integer defaults to 1000
    format_output as FractionFormat defaults to RATIONAL
    include_metadata as Boolean defaults to true

Note: Core Creation Functions
Process called "create_fraction" that takes numerator as Integer and denominator as Integer returns FractionResult:
    Return create_fraction_with_options with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator and options as create_default_fraction_options

Process called "create_fraction_with_options" that takes numerator as Integer and denominator as Integer and options as FractionOptions returns FractionResult:
    If denominator is equal to 0 and not options.allow_zero_denominator:
        Return FractionError with message as "Denominator cannot be zero" and code as "ZERO_DENOMINATOR"
    
    If denominator is equal to 0:
        Return FractionError with message as "Division by zero" and code as "DIVISION_BY_ZERO"
    
    Let fraction be Fraction with:
        numerator as numerator
        denominator as denominator
        metadata as dictionary containing:
            "created_at" as current_time
            "simplified" as false
    
    If options.simplify_automatically:
        Let simplified be simplify_fraction with fraction as fraction
        Match simplified:
            When FractionSuccess with value as simplified_fraction:
                Return FractionSuccess with value as simplified_fraction
            Otherwise:
                Return simplified
    Otherwise:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as fraction

Process called "from_decimal" that takes decimal_value as Float returns FractionResult:
    Return from_decimal_with_options with decimal_value as decimal_value and options as create_default_fraction_options

Process called "from_decimal_with_options" that takes decimal_value as Float and options as FractionOptions returns FractionResult:
    If decimal_value is not finite:
        Return FractionError with message as "Cannot convert non-finite value to fraction" and code as "NON_FINITE_VALUE"
    
    Let (numerator, denominator) be decimal_to_rational with decimal_value as decimal_value and max_precision as options.max_precision
    Return create_fraction_with_options with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator and options as options

Process called "from_string" that takes string_value as String returns FractionResult:
    Return from_string_with_options with string_value as string_value and options as create_default_fraction_options

Process called "from_string_with_options" that takes string_value as String and options as FractionOptions returns FractionResult:
    Let parsed be parse_fraction_string with string as string_value
    Match parsed:
        When FractionSuccess with value as (numerator, denominator):
            Return create_fraction_with_options with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator and options as options
        Otherwise:
            Return parsed

Process called "zero" returns Fraction:
    Return Fraction with:
        numerator as 0
        denominator as 1
        metadata as dictionary containing:
            "created_at" as current_time
            "simplified" as true
            "special" as "zero"

Process called "one" returns Fraction:
    Return Fraction with:
        numerator as 1
        denominator as 1
        metadata as dictionary containing:
            "created_at" as current_time
            "simplified" as true
            "special" as "one"

Process called "negative_one" returns Fraction:
    Return Fraction with:
        numerator as -1
        denominator as 1
        metadata as dictionary containing:
            "created_at" as current_time
            "simplified" as true
            "special" as "negative_one"

Note: Arithmetic Operations
Process called "add" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    Let numerator be (a.numerator multiplied by b.denominator) plus (b.numerator multiplied by a.denominator)
    Let denominator be a.denominator multiplied by b.denominator
    Return create_fraction with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator

Process called "subtract" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    Let numerator be (a.numerator multiplied by b.denominator) minus (b.numerator multiplied by a.denominator)
    Let denominator be a.denominator multiplied by b.denominator
    Return create_fraction with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator

Process called "multiply" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    Let numerator be a.numerator multiplied by b.numerator
    Let denominator be a.denominator multiplied by b.denominator
    Return create_fraction with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator

Process called "divide" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    If b.numerator is equal to 0:
        Return FractionError with message as "Division by zero" and code as "DIVISION_BY_ZERO"
    
    Let numerator be a.numerator multiplied by b.denominator
    Let denominator be a.denominator multiplied by b.numerator
    Return create_fraction with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator

Process called "power" that takes base as Fraction and exponent as Integer returns FractionResult:
    If exponent is equal to 0:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as one
    Otherwise if exponent is equal to 1:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as base
    Otherwise if exponent is greater than 0:
        Let numerator be base.numerator to the power of exponent
        Let denominator be base.denominator to the power of exponent
        Return create_fraction with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator
    Otherwise:
        Let positive_exponent be negative exponent
        Let numerator be base.denominator to the power of positive_exponent
        Let denominator be base.numerator to the power of positive_exponent
        Return create_fraction with numerator as numerator and denominator as denominator

Process called "negate" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Fraction:
    Return Fraction with:
        numerator as negative fraction.numerator
        denominator as fraction.denominator
        metadata as fraction.metadata

Process called "reciprocal" that takes fraction as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    If fraction.numerator is equal to 0:
        Return FractionError with message as "Cannot compute reciprocal of zero" and code as "ZERO_RECIPROCAL"
    
    Return create_fraction with numerator as fraction.denominator and denominator as fraction.numerator

Note: Comparison Operations
Process called "is_equal" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Let simplified_a be simplify_fraction with fraction as a
    Let simplified_b be simplify_fraction with fraction as b
    
    Match simplified_a:
        When FractionSuccess with value as a_simplified:
            Match simplified_b:
                When FractionSuccess with value as b_simplified:
                    Return a_simplified.numerator is equal to b_simplified.numerator and a_simplified.denominator is equal to b_simplified.denominator
                Otherwise:
                    Return false
        Otherwise:
            Return false

Process called "is_less_than" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Let cross_product be (a.numerator multiplied by b.denominator) minus (b.numerator multiplied by a.denominator)
    Let denominator_product be a.denominator multiplied by b.denominator
    Return (cross_product multiplied by denominator_product) is less than 0

Process called "is_greater_than" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return is_less_than with a as b and b as a

Process called "is_less_than_or_equal" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return is_less_than with a as a and b as b or is_equal with a as a and b as b

Process called "is_greater_than_or_equal" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return is_greater_than with a as a and b as b or is_equal with a as a and b as b

Process called "compare" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns Integer:
    If is_equal with a as a and b as b:
        Return 0
    Otherwise if is_less_than with a as a and b as b:
        Return -1
    Otherwise:
        Return 1

Note: Mathematical Functions
Process called "absolute_value" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Fraction:
    Return Fraction with:
        numerator as absolute_value with value as fraction.numerator
        denominator as absolute_value with value as fraction.denominator
        metadata as fraction.metadata

Process called "floor" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Integer:
    Return fraction.numerator divided by fraction.denominator

Process called "ceiling" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Integer:
    Let quotient be fraction.numerator divided by fraction.denominator
    Let remainder be fraction.numerator modulo fraction.denominator
    If remainder is greater than 0:
        Return quotient plus 1
    Otherwise:
        Return quotient

Process called "round" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Integer:
    Let decimal_value be to_decimal with fraction as fraction
    Return round with value as decimal_value

Process called "truncate" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Integer:
    If fraction.numerator is greater than or equal to 0:
        Return floor with fraction as fraction
    Otherwise:
        Return ceiling with fraction as fraction

Process called "modulo" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    Let quotient_result be divide with a as a and b as b
    Match quotient_result:
        When FractionSuccess with value as quotient:
            Let floor_quotient be floor with fraction as quotient
            Let floor_fraction be create_fraction with numerator as floor_quotient and denominator as 1
            Match floor_fraction:
                When FractionSuccess with value as floor_frac:
                    Let product be multiply with a as floor_frac and b as b
                    Match product:
                        When FractionSuccess with value as product_frac:
                            Return subtract with a as a and b as product_frac
                        Otherwise:
                            Return product
                Otherwise:
                    Return floor_fraction
        Otherwise:
            Return quotient_result

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "simplify_fraction" that takes fraction as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    If fraction.numerator is equal to 0:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as zero
    Otherwise if fraction.denominator is equal to 1:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as fraction
    
    Let gcd_value be greatest_common_divisor with a as absolute_value with value as fraction.numerator and b as absolute_value with value as fraction.denominator
    
    If gcd_value is equal to 1:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as fraction
    Otherwise:
        Let simplified_numerator be fraction.numerator divided by gcd_value
        Let simplified_denominator be fraction.denominator divided by gcd_value
        
        Let simplified_metadata be copy_dictionary with dict as fraction.metadata
        Set simplified_metadata["simplified"] to true
        Set simplified_metadata["gcd_used"] to gcd_value
        
        Return FractionSuccess with value as Fraction with:
            numerator as simplified_numerator
            denominator as simplified_denominator
            metadata as simplified_metadata

Process called "normalize_sign" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Fraction:
    If fraction.denominator is less than 0:
        Return Fraction with:
            numerator as negative fraction.numerator
            denominator as negative fraction.denominator
            metadata as fraction.metadata
    Otherwise:
        Return fraction

Process called "is_proper" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return absolute_value with value as fraction.numerator is less than absolute_value with value as fraction.denominator

Process called "is_improper" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return not is_proper with fraction as fraction

Process called "is_unit" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return absolute_value with value as fraction.numerator is equal to 1

Process called "is_zero" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return fraction.numerator is equal to 0

Process called "is_positive" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return (fraction.numerator multiplied by fraction.denominator) is greater than 0

Process called "is_negative" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return (fraction.numerator multiplied by fraction.denominator) is less than 0

Process called "is_integer" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Boolean:
    Return fraction.denominator is equal to 1

Note: Conversion Functions
Process called "to_decimal" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Float:
    Return fraction.numerator divided by fraction.denominator

Process called "to_string" that takes fraction as Fraction returns String:
    Return to_string_with_format with fraction as fraction and format as RATIONAL

Process called "to_string_with_format" that takes fraction as Fraction and format as FractionFormat returns String:
    Match format:
        When DECIMAL:
            Return format_decimal with value as to_decimal with fraction as fraction
        When RATIONAL:
            Return fraction.numerator plus "/" plus fraction.denominator
        When MIXED:
            Return format_mixed with fraction as fraction
        When SCIENTIFIC:
            Return format_scientific with value as to_decimal with fraction as fraction
        When AI_FRIENDLY:
            Return format_ai_friendly with fraction as fraction

Process called "to_mixed_number" that takes fraction as Fraction returns (Integer, Fraction):
    Let whole_part be floor with fraction as fraction
    Let remainder_numerator be fraction.numerator modulo fraction.denominator
    Let remainder_fraction be create_fraction with numerator as remainder_numerator and denominator as fraction.denominator
    
    Match remainder_fraction:
        When FractionSuccess with value as remainder:
            Return (whole_part, remainder)
        Otherwise:
            Return (whole_part, zero)

Note: Advanced Mathematical Functions
Process called "square_root" that takes fraction as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    If is_negative with fraction as fraction:
        Return FractionError with message as "Cannot compute square root of negative number" and code as "NEGATIVE_SQUARE_ROOT"
    
    If is_zero with fraction as fraction:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as zero
    
    Let numerator_sqrt be integer_square_root with value as fraction.numerator
    Let denominator_sqrt be integer_square_root with value as fraction.denominator
    
    If numerator_sqrt is not None and denominator_sqrt is not None:
        Return create_fraction with numerator as numerator_sqrt and denominator as denominator_sqrt
    Otherwise:
        Return FractionError with message as "Cannot compute exact square root" and code as "IRRATIONAL_RESULT"

Process called "cube_root" that takes fraction as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    If is_zero with fraction as fraction:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as zero
    
    Let numerator_cbrt be integer_cube_root with value as fraction.numerator
    Let denominator_cbrt be integer_cube_root with value as fraction.denominator
    
    If numerator_cbrt is not None and denominator_cbrt is not None:
        Return create_fraction with numerator as numerator_cbrt and denominator as denominator_cbrt
    Otherwise:
        Return FractionError with message as "Cannot compute exact cube root" and code as "IRRATIONAL_RESULT"

Process called "factorial" that takes fraction as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    If not is_integer with fraction as fraction:
        Return FractionError with message as "Factorial is only defined for integers" and code as "NON_INTEGER_FACTORIAL"
    
    If is_negative with fraction as fraction:
        Return FractionError with message as "Factorial is not defined for negative numbers" and code as "NEGATIVE_FACTORIAL"
    
    Let n be fraction.numerator
    If n is equal to 0 or n is equal to 1:
        Return FractionSuccess with value as one
    
    Let result be 1
    For i from 2 to n:
        Set result to result multiplied by i
    
    Return create_fraction with numerator as result and denominator as 1

Process called "greatest_common_divisor" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    Let a_int be create_fraction with numerator as a.numerator and denominator as 1
    Let b_int be create_fraction with numerator as b.numerator and denominator as 1
    
    Match a_int:
        When FractionSuccess with value as a_frac:
            Match b_int:
                When FractionSuccess with value as b_frac:
                    Let gcd_numerator be greatest_common_divisor with a as a_frac.numerator and b as b_frac.numerator
                    Let gcd_denominator be least_common_multiple with a as a.denominator and b as b.denominator
                    Return create_fraction with numerator as gcd_numerator and denominator as gcd_denominator
                Otherwise:
                    Return b_int
        Otherwise:
            Return a_int

Process called "least_common_multiple" that takes a as Fraction and b as Fraction returns FractionResult:
    Let a_int be create_fraction with numerator as a.numerator and denominator as 1
    Let b_int be create_fraction with numerator as b.numerator and denominator as 1
    
    Match a_int:
        When FractionSuccess with value as a_frac:
            Match b_int:
                When FractionSuccess with value as b_frac:
                    Let lcm_numerator be least_common_multiple with a as a_frac.numerator and b as b_frac.numerator
                    Let lcm_denominator be greatest_common_divisor with a as a.denominator and b as b.denominator
                    Return create_fraction with numerator as lcm_numerator and denominator as lcm_denominator
                Otherwise:
                    Return b_int
        Otherwise:
            Return a_int

Note: AI-Friendly Functions
Process called "get_ai_metadata" that takes fraction as Fraction returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Let metadata be dictionary containing:
        "type" as "fraction"
        "numerator" as fraction.numerator
        "denominator" as fraction.denominator
        "decimal_value" as to_decimal with fraction as fraction
        "is_proper" as is_proper with fraction as fraction
        "is_improper" as is_improper with fraction as fraction
        "is_unit" as is_unit with fraction as fraction
        "is_zero" as is_zero with fraction as fraction
        "is_positive" as is_positive with fraction as fraction
        "is_negative" as is_negative with fraction as fraction
        "is_integer" as is_integer with fraction as fraction
        "ai_friendly" as true
        "inspection_time" as current_time
    
    Let mixed_result be to_mixed_number with fraction as fraction
    Let whole_part be mixed_result[0]
    Let fractional_part be mixed_result[1]
    Set metadata["mixed_form"] to dictionary containing:
        "whole_part" as whole_part
        "fractional_part" as fractional_part
    
    Return metadata

Process called "format_ai_friendly" that takes fraction as Fraction returns String:
    Let decimal_value be to_decimal with fraction as fraction
    Let mixed_result be to_mixed_number with fraction as fraction
    Let whole_part be mixed_result[0]
    Let fractional_part be mixed_result[1]
    
    If is_zero with fraction as fraction:
        Return "0"
    Otherwise if is_integer with fraction as fraction:
        Return fraction.numerator
    Otherwise if whole_part is equal to 0:
        Return fraction.numerator plus "/" plus fraction.denominator plus " (" plus format_decimal with value as decimal_value plus ")"
    Otherwise:
        Return whole_part plus " " plus fractional_part.numerator plus "/" plus fractional_part.denominator plus " (" plus format_decimal with value as decimal_value plus ")"

Note: Helper Functions
Process called "create_default_fraction_options" that returns FractionOptions:
    Return FractionOptions with:
        simplify_automatically as true
        allow_zero_denominator as false
        max_precision as 1000
        format_output as RATIONAL
        include_metadata as true

Process called "decimal_to_rational" that takes decimal_value as Float and max_precision as Integer returns (Integer, Integer):
    Let tolerance be 1.0 divided by (10 to the power of max_precision)
    Let continued_fraction be compute_continued_fraction with value as decimal_value and max_terms as max_precision
    
    Let numerator be 0
    Let denominator be 1
    Let prev_numerator be 1
    Let prev_denominator be 0
    
    For each term in continued_fraction:
        Let new_numerator be (term multiplied by numerator) plus prev_numerator
        Let new_denominator be (term multiplied by denominator) plus prev_denominator
        
        Set prev_numerator to numerator
        Set prev_denominator to denominator
        Set numerator to new_numerator
        Set denominator to new_denominator
        
        Let approximation be numerator divided by denominator
        If absolute_value with value as (approximation minus decimal_value) is less than tolerance:
            Break
    
    Return (numerator, denominator)

Process called "parse_fraction_string" that takes string as String returns FractionResult:
    Let parts be split_string with string as string and delimiter as "/"
    If length of parts is equal to 2:
        Let numerator_str be parts at index 0
        Let denominator_str be parts at index 1
        
        Let numerator be parse_integer with string as numerator_str
        Let denominator be parse_integer with string as denominator_str
        
        If numerator is not None and denominator is not None:
            Return FractionSuccess with value as (numerator, denominator)
        Otherwise:
            Return FractionError with message as "Invalid fraction format" and code as "INVALID_FORMAT"
    Otherwise:
        Return FractionError with message as "Invalid fraction format" and code as "INVALID_FORMAT"

Process called "format_decimal" that takes value as Float returns String:
    Note: Format float as decimal string with appropriate precision
    Try:
        Note: Handle special cases
        If value is equal to 0.0:
            Return "0.0"
        If value is infinite or value is not a number:
            Return "invalid"
        
        Note: Convert to string with proper precision
        Let abs_value be absolute_value_float with value as value
        Let sign_prefix be ""
        If value is less than 0.0:
            Set sign_prefix to "-"
        
        Note: Determine appropriate decimal places
        Let decimal_places be determine_decimal_places with value as abs_value
        Let formatted be format_float_with_precision with value as abs_value and precision as decimal_places
        
        Return sign_prefix plus formatted
    Catch error:
        Return "0.0"

Process called "format_mixed" that takes fraction as Fraction returns String:
    Let mixed_result be to_mixed_number with fraction as fraction
    Let whole_part be mixed_result[0]
    Let fractional_part be mixed_result[1]
    
    If whole_part is equal to 0:
        Return fractional_part.numerator plus "/" plus fractional_part.denominator
    Otherwise if fractional_part.numerator is equal to 0:
        Return whole_part
    Otherwise:
        Return whole_part plus " " plus fractional_part.numerator plus "/" plus fractional_part.denominator

Process called "format_scientific" that takes value as Float returns String:
    Note: Format float in scientific notation (e.g., 1.23e+04)
    Try:
        Note: Handle special cases
        If value is equal to 0.0:
            Return "0.0e+00"
        If value is infinite or value is not a number:
            Return "invalid"
        
        Let abs_value be absolute_value_float with value as value
        Let sign_prefix be ""
        If value is less than 0.0:
            Set sign_prefix to "-"
        
        Note: Calculate exponent
        Let exponent be 0
        Let mantissa be abs_value
        
        Note: Normalize mantissa to be between 1.0 and 10.0
        While mantissa is greater than or equal to 10.0:
            Set mantissa to mantissa divided by 10.0
            Set exponent to exponent plus 1
        While mantissa is less than 1.0 and mantissa is greater than 0.0:
            Set mantissa to mantissa multiplied by 10.0
            Set exponent to exponent minus 1
        
        Note: Format mantissa and exponent
        Let mantissa_str be format_float_with_precision with value as mantissa and precision as 6
        Let exponent_sign be "+"
        If exponent is less than 0:
            Set exponent_sign to "-"
            Set exponent to negative exponent
        
        Let exponent_str be pad_integer_with_zeros with value as exponent and width as 2
        
        Return sign_prefix plus mantissa_str plus "e" plus exponent_sign plus exponent_str
    Catch error:
        Return "0.0e+00"

Process called "greatest_common_divisor" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Euclidean algorithm for computing GCD
    Let abs_a be absolute_value with value as a
    Let abs_b be absolute_value with value as b
    
    Note: Handle edge cases
    If abs_a is equal to 0:
        Return abs_b
    If abs_b is equal to 0:
        Return abs_a
    
    Note: Euclidean algorithm: gcd(a,b) = gcd(b, a mod b)
    While abs_b is not equal to 0:
        Let remainder be abs_a modulo abs_b
        Set abs_a to abs_b
        Set abs_b to remainder
    
    Return abs_a

Process called "least_common_multiple" that takes a as Integer and b as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: LCM using the identity: lcm(a,b) = |a*b| / gcd(a,b)
    Let abs_a be absolute_value with value as a
    Let abs_b be absolute_value with value as b
    
    Note: Handle edge cases
    If abs_a is equal to 0 or abs_b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    
    Let gcd_value be greatest_common_divisor with a as abs_a and b as abs_b
    Let product be abs_a multiplied by abs_b
    Return product divided by gcd_value

Process called "absolute_value" that takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return absolute value of integer
    If value is less than 0:
        Return negative value
    Otherwise:
        Return value

Process called "integer_square_root" that takes value as Integer returns Optional[Integer]:
    Note: Calculate integer square root using Newton's method
    If value is less than 0:
        Return None
    
    If value is equal to 0 or value is equal to 1:
        Return Some with value as value
    
    Note: Newton's method for integer square root
    Let x be value divided by 2
    Let prev_x be x plus 1
    
    While x is less than prev_x:
        Set prev_x to x
        Set x to (x plus (value divided by x)) divided by 2
    
    Note: Check if result is exact
    If prev_x multiplied by prev_x is equal to value:
        Return Some with value as prev_x
    Otherwise:
        Return None

Process called "integer_cube_root" that takes value as Integer returns Optional[Integer]:
    Note: Calculate integer cube root using Newton's method
    If value is equal to 0 or value is equal to 1:
        Return Some with value as value
    
    Let abs_value be absolute_value with value as value
    
    Note: Newton's method for cube root
    Let x be abs_value divided by 3
    Let prev_x be x plus 1
    
    While x is less than prev_x:
        Set prev_x to x
        Set x to (2 multiplied by x plus (abs_value divided by (x multiplied by x))) divided by 3
    
    Note: Check if result is exact
    If prev_x multiplied by prev_x multiplied by prev_x is equal to abs_value:
        If value is less than 0:
            Return Some with value as negative prev_x
        Otherwise:
            Return Some with value as prev_x
    Otherwise:
        Return None

Process called "compute_continued_fraction" that takes value as Float and max_terms as Integer returns List[Integer]:
    Note: Compute continued fraction representation of a float
    Let result be list containing
    Let x be value
    Let terms_count be 0
    
    While terms_count is less than max_terms and x is not equal to 0.0:
        Let integer_part be floor_float with value as x
        Add integer_part to result
        Set terms_count to terms_count plus 1
        
        Let fractional_part be x minus integer_part
        If fractional_part is less than 0.000001:  Note: Precision threshold
            Break
        
        Set x to 1.0 divided by fractional_part
    
    Return result

Process called "parse_integer" that takes string as String returns Optional[Integer]:
    Note: Parse string to integer with error handling
    If length of string is equal to 0:
        Return None
    
    Let trimmed be trim_whitespace with string as string
    If length of trimmed is equal to 0:
        Return None
    
    Let result be 0
    Let sign be 1
    Let start_index be 0
    
    Note: Handle sign
    If character_at with string as trimmed and index as 0 is equal to "-":
        Set sign to negative 1
        Set start_index to 1
    Otherwise if character_at with string as trimmed and index as 0 is equal to "+":
        Set start_index to 1
    
    Note: Parse digits
    For i from start_index to length of trimmed minus 1:
        Let char be character_at with string as trimmed and index as i
        If is_digit with char as char:
            Let digit_value be char_to_digit with char as char
            Set result to result multiplied by 10 plus digit_value
        Otherwise:
            Return None
    
    Return Some with value as result multiplied by sign

Process called "round" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Round float to nearest integer using round-half-up
    If value is greater than or equal to 0.0:
        Return floor_float with value as (value plus 0.5)
    Otherwise:
        Return ceiling_float with value as (value minus 0.5)

Process called "copy_dictionary" that takes dict as Dictionary[String, Any] returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Note: Create a shallow copy of dictionary
    Let result be dictionary containing
    
    For each key in keys of dict:
        Set result at key key to dict at key key
    
    Return result

Process called "current_time" returns Float:
    Note: Returns current system time in seconds since Unix epoch
    Try:
        Return system_time_seconds
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0

Process called "split_string" that takes string as String and delimiter as String returns List[String]:
    Note: Split string by delimiter into list of substrings
    If length of delimiter is equal to 0:
        Return list containing string
    
    Let result be list containing
    Let current_part be ""
    Let i be 0
    Let string_length be length of string
    Let delimiter_length be length of delimiter
    
    While i is less than string_length:
        Let matches_delimiter be true
        
        Note: Check if delimiter matches at current position
        For j from 0 to delimiter_length minus 1:
            If i plus j is greater than or equal to string_length:
                Set matches_delimiter to false
                Break
            If character_at with string as string and index as (i plus j) is not equal to character_at with string as delimiter and index as j:
                Set matches_delimiter to false
                Break
        
        If matches_delimiter:
            Add current_part to result
            Set current_part to ""
            Set i to i plus delimiter_length
        Otherwise:
            Set current_part to current_part plus character_at with string as string and index as i
            Set i to i plus 1
    
    Note: Add the final part
    Add current_part to result
    Return result

Process called "length" that takes lst as List[Any] returns Integer:
    Note: Return the number of elements in the list
    Try:
        Return system_call_list_length with list as lst
    Catch error:
        Return 0

Process called "Some" that takes value as Any returns Optional[Any]:
    Note: Wrap value in Optional type - CRITICAL for type system correctness
    Return Optional with value as value and has_value as true

Process called "None" returns Optional[Any]:
    Note: Return empty Optional type - CRITICAL for type system correctness
    Return Optional with value as none and has_value as false

Note: Additional helper functions for fractions implementation

Process called "absolute_value_float" that takes value as Float returns Float:
    Note: Return absolute value of float
    If value is less than 0.0:
        Return negative value
    Otherwise:
        Return value

Process called "determine_decimal_places" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Determine appropriate number of decimal places for display
    Let abs_value be absolute_value_float with value as value
    
    If abs_value is greater than or equal to 1.0:
        Return 6
    Otherwise if abs_value is greater than or equal to 0.1:
        Return 8
    Otherwise if abs_value is greater than or equal to 0.01:
        Return 10
    Otherwise:
        Return 12

Process called "format_float_with_precision" that takes value as Float and precision as Integer returns String:
    Note: Format float with specified number of decimal places
    Try:
        Return system_call_format_float with value as value and precision as precision
    Catch error:
        Return float_to_string with value as value

Process called "pad_integer_with_zeros" that takes value as Integer and width as Integer returns String:
    Note: Pad integer with leading zeros to specified width
    Let str_value be integer_to_string with value as value
    Let current_length be length of str_value
    
    If current_length is greater than or equal to width:
        Return str_value
    
    Let padding_needed be width minus current_length
    Let padding be ""
    For i from 0 to padding_needed minus 1:
        Set padding to padding plus "0"
    
    Return padding plus str_value

Process called "floor_float" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Return largest integer less than or equal to value
    Try:
        Return system_call_floor with value as value
    Catch error:
        If value is greater than or equal to 0.0:
            Return truncate_float with value as value
        Otherwise:
            Let truncated be truncate_float with value as value
            If value is not equal to truncated:
                Return truncated minus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return truncated

Process called "ceiling_float" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Return smallest integer greater than or equal to value
    Try:
        Return system_call_ceiling with value as value
    Catch error:
        If value is less than or equal to 0.0:
            Return truncate_float with value as value
        Otherwise:
            Let truncated be truncate_float with value as value
            If value is not equal to truncated:
                Return truncated plus 1
            Otherwise:
                Return truncated

Process called "truncate_float" that takes value as Float returns Integer:
    Note: Truncate float towards zero
    Try:
        Return system_call_truncate with value as value
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback implementation
        If value is greater than or equal to 0.0:
            Return 0  Note: Simplified fallback
        Otherwise:
            Return 0

Process called "trim_whitespace" that takes string as String returns String:
    Note: Remove leading and trailing whitespace
    Let start_index be 0
    Let end_index be length of string
    
    Note: Find first non-whitespace character
    While start_index is less than end_index:
        Let char be character_at with string as string and index as start_index
        If not is_whitespace with char as char:
            Break
        Set start_index to start_index plus 1
    
    Note: Find last non-whitespace character
    While end_index is greater than start_index:
        Let char be character_at with string as string and index as (end_index minus 1)
        If not is_whitespace with char as char:
            Break
        Set end_index to end_index minus 1
    
    If start_index is greater than or equal to end_index:
        Return ""
    
    Return substring_range with string as string and start as start_index and end as end_index

Process called "character_at" that takes string as String and index as Integer returns String:
    Note: Get character at specific index in string
    If index is less than 0 or index is greater than or equal to length of string:
        Return ""
    Try:
        Return system_call_character_at with string as string and index as index
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "is_digit" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if character is a digit (0-9)
    If length of char is not equal to 1:
        Return false
    
    Let ascii_code be char_to_ascii with char as char
    Return ascii_code is greater than or equal to 48 and ascii_code is less than or equal to 57

Process called "char_to_digit" that takes char as String returns Integer:
    Note: Convert digit character to integer value
    If not is_digit with char as char:
        Return 0
    
    Let ascii_code be char_to_ascii with char as char
    Return ascii_code minus 48

Process called "is_whitespace" that takes char as String returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace (space, tab, newline, etc.)
    If length of char is not equal to 1:
        Return false
    
    Let ascii_code be char_to_ascii with char as char
    Note: Space, tab, newline, carriage return, form feed, vertical tab
    Return ascii_code is equal to 32 or ascii_code is equal to 9 or ascii_code is equal to 10 or ascii_code is equal to 13 or ascii_code is equal to 12 or ascii_code is equal to 11

Process called "substring_range" that takes string as String and start as Integer and end as Integer returns String:
    Note: Extract substring from start index to end index (exclusive)
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to 0
    If end is greater than length of string:
        Set end to length of string
    If start is greater than or equal to end:
        Return ""
    
    Try:
        Return system_call_substring_range with string as string and start as start and end as end
    Catch error:
        Return ""

Process called "char_to_ascii" that takes char as String returns Integer:
    Note: Convert character to ASCII code
    Try:
        Return system_call_char_to_ascii with char as char
    Catch error:
        Return 0

Process called "float_to_string" that takes value as Float returns String:
    Note: Convert float to string representation
    Try:
        Return system_call_float_to_string with value as value
    Catch error:
        Return "0.0"

Process called "integer_to_string" that takes value as Integer returns String:
    Note: Convert integer to string representation
    Try:
        Return system_call_integer_to_string with value as value
    Catch error:
        Return "0"

Process called "keys" that takes dict as Dictionary[String, Any] returns List[String]:
    Note: Return list of dictionary keys
    Try:
        Return system_call_dictionary_keys with dict as dict
    Catch error:
        Return list containing

Process called "system_time_seconds" returns Float:
    Note: Returns current system time in seconds since Unix epoch
    Try:
        Return system_call_get_current_time_seconds
    Catch error:
        Return 0.0 